Before any Prequel or Sequel, fans showed up to see Luke, Leia and Han (and chewie/r2). George Lucas did well in the early 2000's with the prequels, it could have been worse we all admittedly proclaimed. And a large majority of the fan-base forgave those faults in the prequels, and accepted them for what they were because they had George's vision behind it.

Fast forward to the last few years and the franchise and its fans become subjected to half-ass characters that money-driven producers created with little to no explanation for who, how and where they end up. But it is Star-Wars and of course, because of previously listed characters we gladly indulged. But to the fan's disappointment, Luke; turned into an "alien milkaholic" , trains a random kid to be stronger than Yoda in a very small time-span then becomes a ghost? Han gets shanked by his spoiled man-child. and Princess Carry Fisher's character becomes a floating space witch who confusingly dies to the very same man-child. It is no less than astonishing, that one of the worlds biggest, most successful pop-culture franchises in history would drop the ball so low.

And George, if by miracle you ever read this comment, I hope that Disney paycheck was worth it.

I thought this was a great movie too, then again I went in with the intention of getting my money's worth, and enjoying it as much as possible.
So if my perception is screwed, I'm sorry, for you, because I had a good time.

I think the last Jedi still has relevance though and I think this movie incorporated it really well, and even if you found the Last Jedi to be worthless I think this movie made it a worth while part of the trilogy.

The Last Jedi brings a lot of the characters to their worst, which then allows them to be redeemed.


As far as Rey's lightsaber, the hilt is part of her staff, and the kyber crystals are from both Luke and Leia's sabers. I don't know if she put it together herself or if she had someone else do it.

I think the only other qualification for her as a Skywalker is that she now has all of Kylo's life force.

But all in all I think this movie was great, and I don't think this movie was wasted on the Last Jedi, I think it cashes in on it.
As far as the lightsaber catching, you can compare it to both Luke throwing the saber, and Kylo throwing the saber. Without TLJ Kylo's throw has less depth, I need to rewatch the trilogy in order again to better explain these things, but this movie makes it look as if the Last Jedi was planned.

snippet.textDisplay: Frankly, I think the Rise of Skywalker was about as good as it could have been under the circumstances, & when looked at on its own, I think it's pretty good.  However,  I'm not willing to cut it the same slack I did for movies like Venom because the extenuating circumstances were entirely of their own making.  Pretty good is a far cry from what it should've been had the whole trilogy been handled properly, & it's even worse when looked at in the context of the rest of the sequel trilogy, & the rest of the franchise.  By all rights, this movie should've been bigger than Endgame, & the best we got was a decent enough film that had to move at 100 miles an hour in order to get through all the story & exposition we needed because it has basically no connection to anything that came before it.  I'm glad it undid so much of the Last Jedi, but I also wouldn't say it feels at all like a follow up to the Force Awakens, either.  I didn't get the impression that much of anything that played out in this movie had been at all set up by either of the previous movies, which is why it has so much exposition to get through.  Practically all of the story threads feel like they only came into play for this movie alone, which, when you're left with what the Last Jedi did, is understandable.  The only thing I'd really believe was planned from 7 was Rey being a Palpatine, but I'm also convinced this would've played out so much better if Palpatine hadn't been in this movie in the flesh.

I really think that The Last Jedi was important, and this movie only solidified that in my mind. Luke made a huge mistake when he let his fear (and Palpatine's influence we now know) get hold of him and he attacked Ben. Luke was immediately guilt ridden, everything he'd worked for in his life literally went up in flames, and this sent him into despair. He literally found the most isolated planet he could and hid away, hid so thoroughly that he blocked himself off from the force. Then he lived there, completely alone with old books and wallowing in his own scared despair for almost 20 years until Rey came along. This random girl he'd never seen before, probably not even in force visions in the past, waltzes up and thrusts Anakin Skywalker's lightsaber into his hands. You were 100% right when you say the man on that planet was not Luke Skywalker. Luke checked out over a decade ago when his fear made him retreat from everything, and he was now holding this reminder of everything he'd run away from, this object steeped in the force. So of course he throws it over his shoulder, he's given up on everything he was and he wants to be alone again, to hide himself away like Yoda once did on Dagobah. Eventually Rey gets through to him, Luke reconnects with the Force for the first time in YEARS when he gets pushed to that point. EVERYthing floods him all at once- the state of the Galaxy, the lack of Han, and one thing he didn't expect- the conflict of Light and Dark inside of Ben.


I think they actually did well with Luke in TLJ, as an arc of redeeming a man so deep in despair that he basically killed himself in all ways but flesh. Then it happens- the Force apparitions can now manifest for him again, and he's joined first by Yoda. That was not a coincidence that he was visited by Yoda, who had run off to a remote planet to hide away from the Galaxy because he had "failed". And Luke in RoS completed the journey of himself after his redemption from TLJ- "A Jedi's weapon deserves more respect." was just as much said to and of himself as it was to Rey. He admitted how wrong he was, urged Rey to not make his same mistake, playing off the old ideological trope of "All it takes for evil to triumph, is for good men to do nothing." However, I DID really hate how Luke just fades away at the end to join the Force for no real reason. Maybe it was something he realized as Obi-Wan did in IV? He'd started Luke down the path, but Luke was still hesitant, and Obi knew how to become one with the Force, so he made the decision to transition- both to push Luke to become serious, and give him the ability to watch over and guide Luke no matter what. So I think that maybe that was the decision for Luke as well- one last grand appearance to rekindle the hope the Skywalker name brought throughout the Galaxy and push Rey to becoming serious.

I also think that's the reason Rey took the name Skywalker at the end, other than what you touched on with the obvious notion that she'd probably be killed for being a Palpatine. It'd be like if someone named Hitler ran for President of Germany, it would not go well. So instead of continuing the namesake of her grandfather she cast that aside, and instead decided to take on the mantle of Skywalker, to make sure that the hope and peace that name stood for remains in the Galaxy. I loved the movie so very much, and I love watching your videos because like you Star Wars is everything to me lol

Luke's character in TLJ wasn't as off and as disrespectful as you might think. He was either emotional or flat out whiney a lot of the time in the original movies. His training from Yoda and Obi-Wan was shake and bake. In the end in the original trilogy, he does the right thing and redeems Anakin Skywalker. But before that he gives into his rage and attacks Vader with fury.
Fast forward to TLJ. He's experienced the loss of his nephew to the Dark Side as well as some of his other students...while the rest were slaughtered. That wrecked him. Luke is a powerful Jedi, but his emotional character was never all that solid. Not like Leia's! So to see him end up as a hermit on a remote location isn't that far fetched. He's wallowing in emotion as he's always done. And Rey redeemed him just as he redeemed his father.
So when we see Luke's Force Ghost in RoS, we're seeing Luke's best self. The Luke he always should have been. It's all been an arc. You just have to take a step back to see it.
#CertainPointOfView

@star wars theory I'm sorry sir, but I have to strongly disagree with you on this review. You probably should watch this video again, and count how many times where you say "I don't know" or "that doesn't make sense" when explaining the bizarre decisions that were made. In a way, this film was doomed the moment Episode 8 was released. They've dug such a deep hole that could never be climbed out of. That's why the pacing of the film is beyond maniacal. They spent most of the film retconning the events of the prior film, and in doing so created major plotholes and inconsistencies. Like the return of Darth Sidious, which makes no sense at all. It was obvious that this was not the villain they originally envisioned. The one line where he repeats a line from ROTS about the "dark side leads to abilities some would consider unnatural" was a lazy and nonsensical explanation of his survival (is cloning now a dark side ability?)


The bizarre kiss between Ben and Rey was out of character, as there was no hint of it at all in the previous films. Yet, no romance between her and Finn (which would have been a lot easier to digest?). I agree with your sentiment about Rey calling herself a Skywalker as another bizarre decision. She's a Palpatine, not a Skywalker; and it completely goes against what Leia said about not being afraid of who she is. That line is a cop-out, and seems like it was tacked on after the initial cut was finished. It's as if they came up with amazing title "The Rise of Skywalker" but had no clear outline how to incorporate the meaning of it in the film itself. I can go on ... but I digress. For an action sci-fi movie, it was fine. For Star Wars fans like you and I .. it's a travesty. They know it too.

I just watched it! Finally!! I have been avoiding YouTube and stuff to avoid spoilers and have been excited for your review!! I’m glad I’m not the only person who enjoyed it!

As for Palpatine’s return, I do believe it was cloning because if I remember correctly when Kylo goes there I saw Palpatine heads in tanks. So there’s that. Also this might be the EU stuff you are referring to, but in the Tarkin book there is some ritual for immortality that involved a master and a apprentice. A bait and vessel. And they would rule for a thousand years. Which definitely seemed like what Palpatine was saying about how all the Sith live in him and when Rey kills him he will transfer his life into her body. I believe the master is the bait, and the apprentice is the vessel they transfer their essence into. Which is why he was so obsessed with Anakin and Luke. Because he wanted the Chosen One or the Chosen One’s son as the vessel.

As for his death, yeah it did seem really quick. Then again there was so much this movie had to do and it only had so much time. Plus like Ian can only do so much with his age. And I guess literally all the Jedi ever including Anakin, where channeling their power through her. So in the end I was ok with it.


Also with Han I think that was just Ben’s imagination. Like him replaying the scene on the bridge with Han in a different way, with a different outcome. Which makes sense because that scene is what has been haunting him. Although it is also insinuated Leia used her power to conjure that imagery for Ben to help him.

Also I really love the concept of the Heir to the Empire rejecting the throne. Like that’s freaking cool.

I always thought Ben had to die if he didn’t turn in the second film. Because in Bloodline you see how the galaxy react to Vader afterwards. Like one person being all like “they are redeemed!” Doesn’t do a lot to make up for genocide and stuff. Like even Leia still had issues with her father. So even if Ben was redeemed, as Supreme Leader he was arguable worse then the Empire because in the EU stuff between films his police is destroy any planet who makes even slight contact with the Resistance. He can’t just get off scot free. He would have ended up in galactic jail or executed. Something like that. He needed to die like Anakin for logistical reasons. Though I would have liked to have seen more of him.

Also one scene I freaking loved was when Rey raises the saber as if to kill Palpatine, but because of her and Ben’s bond she actually sends it him, and the little “shall we?” gesture he makes to the KOR is freaking badass.

With Rey calling herself a Skywalker, I loved that part for a few reasons. First being I always did want her to be a Skywalker, so this is better then nothing. But then also, she was never really a Palpatine. Like she didn’t see him as her grandpa. She saw him as the murderer of her father and mother. The only people she considers family are Finn and Poe, and the Skywalkers. Leia was like a mother, and though she had a rocky relationship with Luke (Rian’s doing, although in the book Rey and Luke have an emotional dance together and there is even film concept art for it). But he and Han were both father figures to her. So in the end when it comes to what family is she apart of, what name would she give? Skywalker of course. And the reason why she is a Skywalker, is because it’s more then just blood. Anyone capable of raising above is capable of being a Skywalker. It is a huge task to accomplish but those we have seen do so, have all been Skywalkers. Anakin rose about the dark side. Luke rose above the dark side. In the end Ben rose above the dark side. And Rey, born of the ultimate evil, rose above as well. This is therefore about the rise of Rey Skywalker. It’s super symbolic, but thematically I ended up happy.

Leia was like a mother, and though she had a rocky relationship with Luke (Rian’s doing, although in the book Rey and Luke have an emotional dance together and there is even film concept art for it). But he and Han were both father figures to her. So in the end when it comes to what family is she apart of, what name would she give? Skywalker of course. And the reason why she is a Skywalker, is because it’s more then just blood. Anyone capable of raising above is capable of being a Skywalker. It is a huge task to accomplish but those we have seen do so, have all been Skywalkers. Anakin rose about the dark side. Luke rose above the dark side. In the end Ben rose above the dark side. And Rey, born of the ultimate evil, rose above as well. This is therefore about the rise of Rey Skywalker. It’s super symbolic, but thematically I ended up happy.

I think Rey calling herself a Skywalker at the end was supposed to show her choosing the light over the darkness. The whole movie, she was utterly terrified that she would fall to the dark side, especially after she found out her real last name. That Palpatine name for her signified all her worst fears of falling to the dark side.
Luke counseling her started with the idea for her that she could choose light or dark, that it wasn't something foregone because of lineage (as a sidenote, I really liked that it was Luke that said that, it brings back the flaw episode 8 introduced that Luke never gave up on Vader but gave up on Ben?). Both Ben and Rey learned that this movie. Each had their own scene that sealed the deal on that lesson. For Ben, it was throwing his lightsaber. For Rey, it was forsaking the name that she feared forced her to adopt the darkness, and instead taking the name that she associated with the light- Skywalker.
